# Important Git Commands

## Check Git Version

```bash
git --version
```

Example

```bash
git --version
```

Output

```text
git version 2.xx.x
```

---

## Initialize a Repository

```bash
git init
```

Creates a new Git repository.

Example

```bash
git init
```

---

## Check Repository Status

```bash
git status
```

Shows modified, staged and untracked files.

---

## Add One File

```bash
git add Main.java
```

---

## Add All Files

```bash
git add .
```

Stages all modified files.

---

## Commit Changes

```bash
git commit -m "Added Login Feature"
```

Creates a snapshot of the project.

---

## View Commit History

```bash
git log
```

Shows all commits.

---

## Push Changes

```bash
git push
```

Uploads local commits to GitHub.

---

## Pull Latest Changes

```bash
git pull
```

Downloads changes from GitHub.

---

## Clone Repository

```bash
git clone <repository-url>
```

Example

```bash
git clone https://github.com/user/project.git
```

Copies the repository to your computer.

---

## Create New Branch

```bash
git branch feature-login
```

---

## View All Branches

```bash
git branch
```

---

## Switch Branch

```bash
git checkout feature-login
```

or

```bash
git switch feature-login
```

---

## Create and Switch Branch

```bash
git checkout -b feature-login
```

---

## Merge Branch

```bash
git merge feature-login
```

Merges the feature branch into the current branch.

---

# .gitignore

Used to ignore files and folders that should not be tracked by Git.

Example

```text
*.class
node_modules/
target/
.idea/
.env
```

